<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFFC4FFC5D495E29854BD18E1" box="[199,1023,1231,1256]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="91193695FFC4FFC5D495E29854BD18E1" blockId="24.[151,1437,151,1653]" box="[199,1023,1231,1256]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D495E298560C18EE" bold="true" box="[199,334,1231,1256]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology.</emphasis>
Species named in reference of its striking bicoloured pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFFC4FFC5D495E2A3550E1A73" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="91193695FFC4FFC5D495E2A3550E1A73" blockId="24.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D495E2A3560D190B" bold="true" box="[199,335,1268,1293]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC4FFC5D505E2A35507190B" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[343,581,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D505E2A35507190B" box="[343,581,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Holopothrips bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the species in the genus with a striking bicoloured body (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC4FFC5D113E2A352D6190A" box="[1345,1428,1268,1293]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) and bears almost equiangular reticulation in the metanotum, without any internal markings (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC4FFC5D086E340526E1936" box="[1236,1324,1303,1328]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
), like the brown-coloured species 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC4FFC5D5FAE36A540C1953" authority="Cavalleri &amp; Kaminski" authorityName="Cavalleri &amp; Kaminski" box="[424,846,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claritibialis">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D5FAE36A550C1953" box="[424,590,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. claritibialis</emphasis>
Cavalleri &amp; Kaminski
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC4FFC5D70BE36A537C1953" authority="Hood" authorityName="Hood" box="[857,1086,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hambletoni">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D70BE36A54BB1953" box="[857,1017,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. hambletoni</emphasis>
Hood
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC4FFC5D026E36A52C01952" authority="Moulton. It" authorityName="Moulton. It" box="[1140,1410,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennatus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D026E36A53B91952" box="[1140,1275,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. pennatus</emphasis>
Moulton. It
</taxonomicName>
is also among the few species with multiple minute tubercles on the dorsolateral sculpture of head. This species shares with 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC4FFC5D573E3D256CA199B" box="[289,392,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D573E3D256CA199B" box="[289,392,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. fulvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having postocular setae minute and head with large eyes and curved cheeks, but is readily distinghished by its fully brown head (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC4FFC5D618E3F055DC19C6" box="[586,670,1447,1472]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), brown abdominal segment VIII and male pore plates occurring on abdominal sternites VI–VIII (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC4FFC5D5B3E39B557619E3" box="[481,564,1484,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–38" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,265,1886]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 32–38. Holopothrips bicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (32) body; (33) head and pronotum; (34) mesonotum; (35) pore plates on sternites VI–VIII; (36) pelta; (37) spermatheca; (38) metanotum, showing the anterior discal setae (black arrows)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445194/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC4FFC5D61AE39B547719E3" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[584,821,1484,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D61AE39B547719E3" box="[584,821,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Holopothrips bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be related to the other seven bicoloured species of the genus whose body is mostly yellow, being distinguished by having the head and abdominal segment VIII fully brown, postocular setae about as long as the diameter of an ocellus and female spermatheca enlarged. A male and a female were studied from leaves of 
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC4FFC5D66BE06E54491A56" box="[569,779,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Myrcia guianensis</emphasis>
collected in the city of Camaçari, 
<collectingRegion id="5362F877FFC4FFC5D0F2E06053A61A56" box="[1184,1252,1591,1616]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Bahia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="E9B17605FFC4FFC5D0A0E060527B1A56" box="[1266,1337,1591,1616]" name="Brazil" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and are believed to belong to the same species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
